<subSubSection pageId="37" pageNumber="38" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="37.[151,1437,151,645]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,548,573]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Etymology.</emphasis>
From the Latin adverb,” 
<emphasis box="[611,643,548,573]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">bis</emphasis>
”, “ 
<emphasis box="[682,704,548,573]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">bi</emphasis>
-” meaning two, and the adjective “ 
<emphasis box="[1100,1183,549,572]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">vittatus</emphasis>
” derived from “ 
<emphasis box="[1367,1417,549,572]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">vitta</emphasis>
”, meaning ribbon or stripe, in reference to the pair of broad dark stripes on the scutum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
